Exercise 4 - Spring Boot REST API (List of Countries)

This exercise demonstrates the implementation of a simple REST API using **Spring Boot 3** that returns a list of countries in JSON format.

📝 Description

In this Spring Boot application, we create a REST endpoint (`/countries`) which returns a list of predefined countries using a controller and service class. The response is served in JSON format. This demonstrates basic use of `@RestController`, `@GetMapping`, dependency injection with `@Autowired`, and returning a list of custom objects in a RESTful way.

📥 Sample Input (Request)

GET http://localhost:8080/countries

You can test this using Postman or a web browser after running the application.

📤 Sample Output (Response)
[
  {
    "code": "IN",
    "name": "India"
  },
  {
    "code": "US",
    "name": "United States"
  },
  {
    "code": "JP",
    "name": "Japan"
  }
]

⚙️ Technologies & Tools Used
Java 17

Spring Boot 3.5.3

Spring Web

Eclipse IDE 

Embedded Apache Tomcat (default port 8080)

🚀 How to Run
Open the project in Eclipse or IntelliJ.

Run the main application class:
SpringRestHandsonApplication.java

Open browser or Postman and visit:
http://localhost:8080/countries
